$CATEGORY: CIT/M4/week-9/9-6-how-human-biases-get-encoded-into-ai-training-data

::q1:: When we say a human bias has been "encoded" into an AI system's training data, what has happened? {
~The AI has been deliberately programmed by engineers to behave unfairly toward certain groups.#No — encoding is not deliberate programming; it happens when biased human decisions are recorded as data the AI learns from.
~The AI has detected a pattern in the real world that accurately reflects how society works.#No — the pattern may reflect historical discrimination rather than an objective fact about the world.
=A biased human decision has been turned into a data pattern, and the AI treats that pattern as fact.#Correct — encoding means the bias has been converted into numbers, labels, or text the AI learns from, with no awareness the pattern came from an unfair human choice.
~The AI has made so many mistakes that it has created its own new form of bias unrelated to human input.#No — encoded bias originates from human decisions in the data, not from the AI inventing errors independently.
#### Tests the definition of "encoding" bias into training data (corpus §5.1).
}

::q2:: A company hires workers to label customer reviews as positive, negative, or neutral. Some workers consistently mark sarcastic reviews as positive because they miss the tone. Which encoding mechanism does this illustrate? {
=Labelling bias — the workers' incorrect judgment calls have attached wrong tags to the data, and the AI will learn those errors.#Correct — labelling bias occurs when the prejudices or mistakes of human annotators are baked into the tags attached to training examples.
~Historical bias — the reviews accurately record a past period when customers were more sarcastic, so the data is unfair.#No — historical bias refers to faithfully recording an unfair history, not to annotators misreading tone in current data.
~Selection bias — the company only collected reviews from customers who tend to be sarcastic, leaving other groups out.#No — selection bias is about who or what is represented in the dataset, not about how items are tagged once collected.
~Feedback loop amplification — the AI's earlier predictions about sarcasm are now influencing which reviews the workers label.#No — a feedback loop requires the AI's outputs to be recycled as new training data; here the AI has not yet been deployed.
#### Tests recognition of labelling bias and its mechanism (corpus §5.2).
}

::q3:: An AI system used in US hospitals to identify patients needing extra care was found to systematically underestimate the health needs of Black patients. Investigators traced the problem to the system's use of healthcare spending as a proxy measure for health needs. Because Black patients had historically been less likely to receive care for the same level of illness, their records showed lower spending — not lower need. Which encoding mechanism best explains why this disparity entered the AI? {
~Labelling bias — clinicians who tagged patient records applied different diagnostic thresholds to different demographic groups, attaching inaccurate health labels.#No — the issue is not inconsistent tagging by clinicians; the data accurately recorded spending patterns already shaped by prior unequal access to care. That is not a labelling mistake — it is an accurate record of an unjust history.
~Selection bias — Black patients were under-represented in the hospital's training dataset, leaving the AI under-trained on their health patterns.#No — the training data included Black patients; the problem was what the data showed about them (lower spending due to prior undercare), not that they were absent from the dataset.
~Feedback loop amplification — the AI's earlier predictions about patient risk were recycled as ground-truth labels for the next version of the model.#No — this describes a retraining cycle; the problem here is an original bias baked into the first training dataset, before any deployment or retraining loop occurred.
=Historical bias — the data accurately recorded decades of unequal access to care, and the AI treated that historical disparity as a template for predicting future health needs.#Correct — historical bias means accurate data can still encode injustice when the history it records was itself discriminatory. The AI reproduced past inequality rather than measuring actual current need (corpus §5.3, §7).
#### Tests example-to-mechanism recall using the healthcare proxy variable case: historical bias as the encoding mechanism (LO3, corpus §7 healthcare pattern).
}

::q4:: Early commercial facial recognition systems had significantly higher error rates for darker-skinned women than for lighter-skinned men. The developers had not intended this disparity. What is the most likely encoding mechanism? {
~Labelling bias — the human workers who tagged the face images used different quality standards for different demographic groups.#No — while labelling bias is possible, the corpus specifically attributes this disparity to the composition of the dataset, not to inconsistent tagging practices.
=Selection bias — the training data over-represented lighter-skinned male faces, leaving the AI under-trained on darker-skinned women and producing worse performance for them.#Correct — selection (representation) bias occurs when the training dataset does not represent all groups the AI will later encounter, leading to unequal real-world performance (corpus §5.4).
~Feedback loop amplification — the AI's earlier incorrect predictions about darker-skinned women were fed back as training data, widening the error gap over time.#No — the error appeared on first deployment, before any feedback cycle; the root cause was the original training dataset composition, not a retraining loop.
~Historical bias — past discrimination meant fewer photos of darker-skinned women existed anywhere, so no dataset could have included them fairly.#No — the issue was where developers chose to source training data (public internet datasets skewed toward one demographic), not an absolute scarcity of such photos in the world.
#### Tests example-to-mechanism recall using the canonical facial recognition case: selection/representation bias as the root cause (LO3, corpus §5.4).
}

::q5:: A team building a loan-approval AI finds that data reviewers consistently remove repayment-success labels on applications from lower-income zip codes — expecting high default rates there. Engineers later retrain the AI on its own approval decisions without auditing those decisions for accuracy. Which two cognitive biases are operating, and why does each retraining cycle make the AI's error worse rather than better? {
=Confirmation bias (9.3) — reviewers filtered out labels that contradicted their expectations; automation bias (9.5) — engineers accepted AI outputs as ground truth, so each retrain cycles biased decisions back in as labels, compounding the skew.#Correct — confirmation bias shapes which labels survive quality review (corpus §5.7 ¶1); automation bias allows biased AI decisions to become the next version's training data (§5.7 ¶2). Each cycle amplifies rather than corrects the initial bias, because the AI's prior mistakes become the next iteration's ground truth (LO4 + LO5).
~Anchoring bias (9.4) — reviewers anchored to the first applications they labelled and adjusted too little; historical bias — engineers re-encoded historical zip-code lending patterns, so retraining simply replays the original history with no amplification.#No — anchoring bias explains over-reliance on a first data point, not filtering based on a group-level prior belief; and the engineers' behaviour is automation bias (9.5). Critically, the scenario describes a self-amplifying loop: each cycle produces worse outputs, not a flat replay of original history.
~Automation bias (9.5) — reviewers over-trusted a prior AI to identify labelling errors; selection bias — engineers made the training set less representative with each retrain, shrinking coverage rather than compounding error.#No — there is no prior AI at the labelling stage; the reviewers are making human judgment calls (confirmation bias). And selection bias describes the initial composition of training data, not an amplifying retraining loop.
~Confirmation bias (9.3) — engineers accepted AI outputs that confirmed their expectations about zip codes; anchoring bias (9.4) — reviewers anchored to early labels and adjusted too little as new data arrived.#No — the engineers' failure is accepting AI outputs without audit, which is automation bias (9.5), not confirmation bias. The reviewers' failure is filtering based on a group-level prior belief about zip codes, which is confirmation bias (9.3), not anchoring.
#### Tests LO4 (confirmation bias + automation bias reinforcing encoding, corpus §5.7) and LO5 (feedback loop amplifies bias over successive retrains; not a single-pass entry).
}

::q6:: This topic describes several mechanisms through which human biases enter AI training data, and mentions a structured approach to help practitioners critically evaluate AI outputs rather than relying on cognitive shortcuts. What is the name of that structured framework, which will be introduced in Topics 9.7–9.9? {
~The Seven-Step Trace#No — the seven-step trace (corpus §6) is a tool for making a specific system's encoding path visible; it is not the name of the structured practitioner framework introduced in Topics 9.7–9.9.
~The Calibrated Trust Model#No — calibrated trust (Topic 9.5) describes the goal of appropriate automation reliance; it is not the name of the structured framework introduced in Topics 9.7–9.9.
=The Judgment Framework#Correct — Topics 9.7–9.9 introduce the Judgment Framework as the structured approach for critically evaluating AI outputs and managing encoding bias risks.
~The Encoding Audit Protocol#No — this is not a named framework in the curriculum; the correct term for the structured approach coming in Topics 9.7–9.9 is the Judgment Framework.
#### Tests LO6 — naming the Judgment Framework as the structured approach for managing encoding bias risks (corpus §8).
}
